<DocsLayout title="API Reference">
  <h1>API Reference</h1>
  <p>
    EncodeSwarmr exposes a REST API at <code>/api/v1</code>. The complete OpenAPI 3.1 specification is served at <code>/api/v1/openapi.json</code> and can be imported directly into Postman, Insomnia, or any OpenAPI-compatible tool. A rendered interactive reference is available at <code>/api/v1/docs</code> (Swagger UI) when the Controller is running.
  </p>

  <h2>Response Envelope</h2>
  <p>
    All successful responses wrap their payload in a standard envelope:
  </p>
  <pre><code>&#123; "data": &#123; ... &#125;, "meta": &#123; "request_id": "..." &#125; &#125;</code></pre>
  <p>
    Error responses follow RFC 9457 (Problem Details for HTTP APIs):
  </p>
  <pre><code>&#123;
  "type": "https://encodeswarmr.dev/errors/not-found",
  "title": "Resource Not Found",
  "status": 404,
  "detail": "Job with ID 'abc123' was not found",
  "instance": "/api/v1/jobs/abc123"
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h2>Resource Groups</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Group</th><th>Base Path</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>auth</strong></td><td><code>/auth</code></td><td>Login, logout, OIDC token exchange, session refresh.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>sources</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/sources</code></td><td>Register, list, and delete media source files. Includes batch import sub-resource.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>jobs</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/jobs</code></td><td>Create, list, get, cancel, and retry encoding jobs. Includes live log streaming and chunk progress.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>agents</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/agents</code></td><td>List agents, get agent details, disable, approve, and push upgrades.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>analysis</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/analysis</code></td><td>Retrieve MediaInfo, HDR metadata, and loudness results for an analysed source.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>webhooks</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/webhooks</code></td><td>Create and manage outbound webhook subscriptions and view delivery history.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>variables</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/variables</code></td><td>Global key-value store accessible from flow nodes and templates.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>templates</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/templates</code></td><td>Create and manage job templates that bundle source patterns, flows, and output rules.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>schedules</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/schedules</code></td><td>Create cron-based schedules that auto-submit jobs or trigger batch imports.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>presets</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/presets</code></td><td>List, create, update, and delete encoding presets.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>plugins</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/plugins</code></td><td>List installed plugins, install from registry, enable/disable, and view plugin logs.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>api-keys</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/api-keys</code></td><td>Generate and revoke API keys with scoped permissions.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>notifications</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/me/notifications</code></td><td>Manage notification channels (email, Slack, Pushover) and view notification history.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>estimate</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/estimate</code></td><td>Request cost and time estimates for a job before submission.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>upgrade</strong></td><td><code>/api/v1/agent/upgrade/check</code></td><td>Agent self-upgrade check: query available versions and initiate upgrade.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Example Workflow</h2>
  <p>
    The following six steps demonstrate a complete encode workflow using the API from the command line.
  </p>

  <h3>1. Authenticate</h3>
  <pre><code>curl -X POST https://controller/auth/login \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '&#123;"username":"admin","password":"changeme"&#125;' \
  -c cookies.txt

# Response sets a session cookie in cookies.txt
# Alternatively, use an API key (see below) to skip this step.</code></pre>

  <h3>2. Submit a Job</h3>
  <pre><code>curl -X POST https://controller/api/v1/jobs \
  -b cookies.txt \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '&#123;
    "source_id": "src_abc123",
    "pipeline": &#123;
      "type": "preset",
      "preset": "1080p-x265-quality"
    &#125;,
    "output": &#123;
      "path": "/mnt/output/&#123;source_name&#125;.mkv"
    &#125;,
    "priority": 7
  &#125;'

# Response: &#123;"data":&#123;"id":"job_xyz","status":"queued",...&#125;&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>3. Poll Job Status</h3>
  <pre><code>curl https://controller/api/v1/jobs/job_xyz \
  -b cookies.txt

# Response:
&#123;
  "data": &#123;
    "id": "job_xyz",
    "status": "running",
    "progress_pct": 42,
    "fps": 28.4,
    "eta_seconds": 3840,
    "agent_id": "agent_gpu01"
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>4. Stream Live Logs</h3>
  <pre><code>curl -N https://controller/api/v1/jobs/&lt;job-uuid&gt;/log/stream \
  -b cookies.txt \
  -H "Accept: text/event-stream"

# Server-Sent Events stream:
# data: &#123;"ts":"2024-11-14T10:05:01Z","line":"frame= 1440 fps= 28 q=24.0..."\&#125;
# data: &#123;"ts":"2024-11-14T10:05:02Z","line":"frame= 1468 fps= 28 q=24.0..."\&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>5. List Agents</h3>
  <pre><code>curl https://controller/api/v1/agents \
  -b cookies.txt

# Response:
&#123;
  "data": [
    &#123;
      "id": "agent_gpu01",
      "hostname": "render-box-01",
      "status": "busy",
      "current_job": "job_xyz",
      "gpu": "NVIDIA RTX 4090",
      "version": "2.4.1"
    &#125;
  ],
  "meta": &#123;"total": 1&#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>6. Approve an Agent</h3>
  <pre><code>curl -X POST https://controller/api/v1/agents/agent_gpu01/approve \
  -b cookies.txt

# Response: 204 No Content
# The agent transitions from pending to approved and begins accepting jobs.</code></pre>

  <h2>API Key Authentication</h2>
  <p>
    API keys are the recommended authentication method for automation and CI/CD pipelines. Keys can be scoped to specific resource groups and operations.
  </p>

  <h3>Create an API Key</h3>
  <pre><code>curl -X POST https://controller/api/v1/api-keys \
  -b cookies.txt \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '&#123;
    "name": "ci-pipeline",
    "scopes": ["jobs:write", "sources:read", "presets:read"],
    "expires_at": "2025-12-31T23:59:59Z"
  &#125;'

# Response:
&#123;
  "data": &#123;
    "id": "key_abc",
    "name": "ci-pipeline",
    "key": "eswr_live_abc123...",   // shown once; store securely
    "scopes": ["jobs:write", "sources:read", "presets:read"],
    "expires_at": "2025-12-31T23:59:59Z"
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <h3>Use an API Key</h3>
  <pre><code>export API_KEY="eswr_live_abc123..."

curl https://controller/api/v1/jobs \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $API_KEY"</code></pre>
  <p>
    The <code>Authorization: Bearer</code> header is accepted on every endpoint. Session cookies and OIDC tokens use the same header format — the Controller identifies the credential type from the token prefix (<code>eswr_live_</code> for API keys, <code>eswr_test_</code> for sandbox keys).
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
